But knowing who is winning is first and foremost to knowing what you need to do to win, yes?
We might not even need deep learning for that part.
Right? Then we can train a reinforcement model "fairly easily" based on if certain actions increase the score.
Oh my wait this seems like the right approach

The first thing we should do independently of playing any game is train a model that can accurately predict the winner while only having vision from one side, i.e. red player model only sees what red player sees, computes a score, blue player model same thing, whoever actually wins in the replay should have a higher score.

But probably taking a vector of position features and learned evaluator score, we can then write a neural net to predict the best way forward. And here, size is no object, since we could literally have an output vector size 1000 with all the probabilities we should do whatever action.

So, I think the best way to train this model might be to learn an evaluator from the replays (each replay provides 2 examples), then to use that evaluator to learn a policy. Searching for a policy is probably still too expensive.

package com.google.challenges; public class Answer { public static int answer(int food, int[][] grid) { int val = helper(food, grid, grid[0].length - 1, grid.length - 1); return val; } public static int helper(int food, int[][] grid, int x, int y) { if (food < 0){ return -1; } if (x == 0){ for(int i = 1; i <= y; i++){ food -= grid[0][i]; } return Math.max(food, -1); } if (y == 0){ for(int i = 1; i <= x; i++){ food -= grid[i][0]; } return Math.max(food, -1); } int right = helper(food - grid[x][y], grid, x - 1, y); int left = helper(food - grid[x][y], grid, x, y - 1); if (right < 0){ return left; } else { if (left < 0){ return right; } return Math.min(right, left); } } }

I teach calculus armed with a roll of toilet paper and an overactive imagination. But before I get into that delightful tale, I have to go on a slight tangent. First, it’s important to note that people generally don’t push themselves to the point of burning out – that’s essentially axiomatic. Second, if teaching calculus hasn’t made it obvious, I like math. Therefore, I shouldn’t be surprised, but I’m still slightly crestfallen whenever people tell me that they aren’t taking AP Calculus because they think they will struggle. Imagine my delight, though, when someone came to me, torn between math classes because calculus seemed difficult, but statistics seemed boring! Finally, I had a chance to show someone what I thought about calculus. So I tried to give a simple explanation that would convince this sophomore going-to-be junior that calculus wasn’t going to be an insurmountable challenge. “Well… The basic idea of an integral is that if you have enough infinitesimal values, they sum to a normal number. Intuitive enough, right?” Generally speaking, a blank stare is not the reaction I hope to see in the people I tutor. I racked my brains for a minute, and, like any other logical person under duress, I concluded that the solution was in the bathroom. Rushing into the bathroom, I noticed a mop bucket in the corner, along with a cart of cleaning supplies – the janitor had been there recently. Perfect. And so, with all the urgency of a conventional bathroom-rusher, I ran straight into a stall and grabbed the fresh roll of toilet paper. Then I left. Armed with my Excalibur of mathematical education that I had pulled out of the dispenser, I was ready to slay the monster known to me simply as “fear of calculus.” I rolled out the first square, the first step to overcoming calculus consternation. “So, let’s assume that this sheet has no thickness. So, we can agree it has no volume.” I stacked on another sheet. “Does it have a volume now? Right, no, it really doesn’t seem like it does.” I looked up from my two sheets of toilet paper to a quizzical, I-question-your-sanity look. But don’t worry! I’ve gotten used to the initial embarrassment, and I’m quite pleased to report that I generally get to watch it transform into a look that states “That’s brilliant.” “Well, take a look at the rest of this roll. I can’t count the number of sheets still on it, how about you? But it’s clearly got a volume. Do you see where I’m going with this?” The pieces were all clicking together now, and I could almost see them fitting together in my pupil’s mind. “Oh, and by the way, this is the hardest thing you will do in first year calculus.” That day, I taught someone the theory behind integration, and convinced them to take AP Calculus. Today, she’s having very little trouble and even enjoys the class, as I’m reminded whenever I ask her how she’s doing with it. As it turns out, a good analogy can simplify calculus a great deal, and toilet paper makes for a surprisingly good example. I could have kept teaching about rotations of solids, infinitesimal values, or, if I had two-ply, also discussed limits. All it would have taken is a few more assumptions and a couple demonstrations, and it would have been fantastic. I challenge the idea that there are things in the world too arcane to ever understand. I challenge the phrase “It’s rocket science to me” in myself and in anyone I meet, because I don’t think the concept ever applies. I hope to continue passing creativity, passion, and accessibility from person to person. I challenge myself to think, to learn, to know, and to facilitate that experience for others, because I believe that everything can be comprehended with just a little bit of toilet paper.
